tools: write-scripts, generate-images, generate-audio, transcribe-audio
args: articleFile: Path to the text file with the article content
args: dir: Directory to save the created files to

Call these tools in this exact order:
1. write-scripts with articleFile=${articleFile} and dir=${dir}
2. generate-images with dir=${dir}
3. generate-audio with dir=${dir}
4. transcribe-audio with dir=${dir}

---
name: write-scripts
tools: sys.read, sys.write
args: articleFile: Path to the article text file
args: dir: Directory to save story files

Read ${articleFile} using sys.read.
Based on the content, write a TL;DR script for a social video (max 100 words, no emojis, spoken conversational style).
Split the script into exactly 3 parts of similar length.
Write Part 1 to ${dir}/story-1.txt using sys.write.
Write Part 2 to ${dir}/story-2.txt using sys.write.
Write Part 3 to ${dir}/story-3.txt using sys.write.

---
name: generate-images
tools: sys.read, sys.download, github.com/gptscript-ai/image-generation
args: dir: Directory containing story files

Read ${dir}/story-1.txt, ${dir}/story-2.txt, and ${dir}/story-3.txt using sys.read.
For each story part:
1. Call imageGeneration with the story text as prompt and size 1024x1792 to get an image URL.
2. Use sys.download to download that URL and save it to the local path.

Save images to:
- Story 1 image → ${dir}/b-roll-1.png
- Story 2 image → ${dir}/b-roll-2.png
- Story 3 image → ${dir}/b-roll-3.png

---
name: generate-audio
tools: sys.read, github.com/nw0rn/text2speech-gptscript
args: dir: Directory containing story files

Read ${dir}/story-1.txt, ${dir}/story-2.txt, and ${dir}/story-3.txt using sys.read.
Generate text-to-speech audio for each:
- Story 1 text → output_file: ${dir}/voiceover-1
- Story 2 text → output_file: ${dir}/voiceover-2
- Story 3 text → output_file: ${dir}/voiceover-3

---
name: transcribe-audio
tools: github.com/dejwid/speech2text-gptscript
args: dir: Directory containing voiceover files

Transcribe each audio file with word-level timestamps:
- file: ${dir}/voiceover-1.mp3 → output: ${dir}/voiceover-1.txt
- file: ${dir}/voiceover-2.mp3 → output: ${dir}/voiceover-2.txt
- file: ${dir}/voiceover-3.mp3 → output: ${dir}/voiceover-3.txt
